weibo$train_id <- sample(c("train", "valid"), nrow(weibo), replace = TRUE)

Introduction

In late February of this year, the Korean government announced they were going to install an American-made anti-missile system in Korea, using land donated by the Korean company Lotte. Chinese citizens and the government were worried that this anti-missile system, called THAAD, could be used to spy on the Chinese government and military. In response to Koreas announcement, Chinese citizens heavily protested Lottes products and stores, travel to Korea, and Korean celebrities.

There was a lot of nationalism during this period, with people saying, Why would any Chinese person want to leave the country? China is strong, too and promoting Chinese celebrities and brands.

When I was in China last semester, I was looking on Weibo (Chinese Twitter) and saw this post:

When I first saw this post, I was really confused. What is going on to make Chinese people hate on Korean celebrities?? As I read more into this Lotte Incident, as its called in China, I got a better understanding of why and how Chinese people were protesting everything.

Seeing how this incident even affected Korean celebrities Weibo pages, I wanted to see if I could look at celebrities who were poopular in Korea (both Chinese and Korean celebrities under contract in Korea) and see if I could see if any characteristics of their Weibo posts were indicative of whether that post was from before or after the announcement of the anti-missile system.

X <- term_df_to_matrix(token_df)
y <- weibo$after
X_train <- X[weibo$train_id == "train",]
y_train <- y[weibo$train_id == "train"]

model <- cv.glmnet(X, y, nfolds = 5, family = "binomial")

weibo$after_pred <- predict(model, newx = X, type = "class")
tapply(weibo$after_pred == weibo$after, weibo$train_id, mean)
##     train     valid 
## 0.5686275 0.5961538

What happened here is every value in my after_pred category is 0, and that happens to lead to an accuracy rate of 59.2%. Can I do better than this?

model2 <- glm(after ~ poly(last, 6) + idol, data = weibo, subset = train_id == "train", family = binomial(link = "logit"))
## Warning: glm.fit: fitted probabilities numerically 0 or 1 occurred
weibo$after_pred2 <- predict(model2, newdata = weibo, type = "response")
weibo$after_pred2 <- as.numeric(weibo$after_pred2 > 0.5)
tapply(weibo$after_pred2 == weibo$after, weibo$train_id, mean)
##     train     valid 
## 0.7647059 0.5769231

Well, the computer yelled at me, but I got a slightly better accuracy rate on both the validatio and training sets, likely due to putting in the number of days since a celebrity last posted.

Reflection

Since I collected this data myself, I know exactly what each post says (except for the super long onesI didnt actually read those), and I can tell why glmnet was not able to get any unique characteristics from the text of the posts alone.

  1. Celebrities social media is really boring

Unless youre there for the pictures, which I didnt include, all of the posts are just celebrities promoting themselves or saying how thankful they are for their fans. I saw one nationalist post from a Chinese celebrity after the Lotte Incident started, but that was literally it.

  1. Korean people dont know Chinese. Or use Weibo

I only found 9 celebrities who were popular on Weibo and posted often. Of them, 3 were Chinese. I only had 103 posts total, which really wasnt enough for analysis.
